{"key":"processedPost-12286508","value":{"id":12286508,"first":12286410,"last":12286508,"when":1269784367,"utime":"03/28/10 04:52 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>SpinyPine44 said:</b><br />I was planning on just dropping a tissue sample into a jar of rye and letting it colonize.&nbsp; I would then do a G2G transfer and use all those jars to make a monotub.&nbsp; After the monotub fruits I would continue the same steps and keep doing it for X number of grows.&nbsp; Would this give me better and better fruiting traits since I would be cloning the biggest fruits each time?<br /></blockquote><br /><br />No, it would result in senescence and very poor performance.&nbsp; You want to clone young, rapidly growing fruits from first flush, and then save the culture in the refrigerator for future use.&nbsp; A better plan is to isolate a really good strain and keep it on master slants to use essentially forever.<br />RR","title":"Re: Cloning question"}}